    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>A Starless Night</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Jay M Pasachoff letter says 92nd Street Y campers should not have missed out on a night under the stars just because of fear of West Nile virus (July 15 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The stars don't show through the roof of the 92nd Street Y (''Camping In, and Leaving the Bugs Out,'' front page, July 15), and the students are the poorer for their lack of outdoor experience. The inspiration that children get from the glorious night sky -- which now includes a comet visible with binoculars -- can motivate them and lead to improved study habits.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>The stars don't show through the roof of the 92nd Street Y (''Camping In, and Leaving the Bugs Out,'' front page, July 15), and the students are the poorer for their lack of outdoor experience. The inspiration that children get from the glorious night sky -- which now includes a comet visible with binoculars -- can motivate them and lead to improved study habits.</p>
        <p>While avoiding the West Nile virus is important, the increased hazard of city traffic over that of an outdoor campground might even outweigh the virus risk.</p>
        <p>JAY M. PASACHOFF  Williamstown, Mass., July 15, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a professor of astronomy at Williams College.</p>
      </block>
